assets.headline: Investors quake as they realise central banks no longer have their backs
assets.indexHeadline: Central banks leave investors in the cold
assets.theAbstract: A further cause for unease is the change at the top of the Fed, with the somewhat inscrutable Jerome Powell replacing the ever-conciliatory Janet Yellen.

relatedImages.description: The Board of Governors of the Federal Reserve seal is displayed on the floor outside the board room in Washington, D.C., U.S., on Monday, Feb. 5, 2018. Jerome Powell, sworn in as the 16th chairman of the Fed, is inheriting a U.S. economy in its third-longest expansion on record, with unemployment and inflation near historically low levels. Photographer: Andrew Harrer/Bloomberg
Investors realised that, for the first time in nearly a decade, the Fed didn't have their back.
Jerome Powell, chairman of the US Federal Reserve, takes the oath of office in Washington on Monday.

assets.headline: Prostate cancer focus shifts from finding it early to preventing its advance
assets.indexHeadline: Prostate researchers point to baldness and booze
assets.theAbstract: Prostate cancer testing is now common, but how do baldness, booze, and ejaculations affect its aggressiveness? New research has some preliminary findings.

relatedImages.description: Until we can tell the tigers from the pussycats, many men will undergo unnecessary treatment and we’ll have a lot of older men made miserable by the side effects,  Graham  Giles
Balding by the age of 20 appears to raise the risk of a man developing an aggressive prostate cancer later in life
Once you have prostate cancer, smoking may prompt it to become aggressive.
How body shape changes may be a risk factor for advanced prostate cancer decades later.
There's a chance red and white wine may be protective against advanced prostate cancer.
Sexual activity exercises the prostate, sweeps its ducts clean and may just have a protective effect.
Most men in their sixties will have a microscopic form of prostate cancer and there aren't accurate tools to predict whose cancer will stay indolent and whose will become active.
Most men in their sixties will have a microscopic form of prostate cancer and there aren't accurate tools to predict whose cancer will stay indolent and whose will become active.
“I get asked the same question every day. Men want to know what they can do for their prostate health,” says Prof Nathan Lawrentschuk.
Funded by the National Health and Medical Research Council, the project is based at Cancer Council of Victoria and includes well-known urologist Professor Damien Bolton.

assets.headline: Jay Weatherill's $800m virtual power plant may be a game changer
assets.indexHeadline: Why SA's virtual power plant may be a game changer
assets.theAbstract: SA Premier Jay Weatherill's announcement of an $800 million, 250MW virtual power plant could be a game changer - if the Weatherill government wins next month's state election.

relatedAssets.title: Simon Hackett Tweet Tesla VPS
relatedAssets.embedCode:
Yes, for a $30m loan for the first 1100 sites only. It’s fabulous stuff but I’m unclear on the details of the bridge to the other 48500 sites. Keen to see a vendor neutral tender for those once the 1100 are proven up. Can’t wait to see it happen!

— Simon Hackett (@simonhackett) February 4, 2018

relatedImages.description: AGL Energy's virtual power plant trial in Salisbury in Adelaide's north - the scene when federal Energy and Environment Minister Josh Frydenberg's press conference was crashed by SA Premier Jay Weatherill.
South Australian Premier Jay Weatherill (left) and Opposition Leader Stephen Marshall at the SA Press Club for the leaders' public debate in Adelaide on Friday.
South Australian Liberal leader Stephen Marshall (pictured with Prime Minister Malcolm Turnbull) has an alternative plan to subsidise home batteries, which could morph into a virtual power plant.

SA Premier Jay Weatherill's $800 million virtual power plant plan could be a game changer for the power grid. Weatherill is pictured touring the new Tesla battery site during the launch of Tesla's 100 megawatt lithium-ion battery at Jamestown, north of Adelaide in December.
